        <dc:creator><![CDATA[@paul]]></dc:creator>
        <description><![CDATA[
          <p><a href="https://sebiik.github.io/community.axoloti.com.backup/u/paul">@paul</a> wrote:</p>
          <blockquote>
              <p>hi sputnki,<br>sure. The 595 Register is a 8bit register. Every bit stands for an output, which you can turn on/off (0/1). So you can turn on/off every output.  </p>

<h2>Example Script (one 74HC595):</h2>

<p>uint8_t *txbuf;</p>

<p>void setup(void){</p>

<pre><code>static uint8_t _txbuf[32] __attribute__ ((section (".sram2")));
txbuf = _txbuf;</code></pre>

<p>}</p>

<p>void loop(void){<br>	spiSelect(&amp;SPID1);<br>	txbuf[0] = 0b10010001;  // turns output 1,4 &amp; 8 high, else low<br>  	spiSend(&amp;SPID1,1,txbuf);<br>  	spiUnselect(&amp;SPID1);<br>	chThdSleepMilliseconds(1);<br>}</p>

<p>check this patch: <a class="attachment" href="//community.axoloti.com/uploads/default/original/1X/da93efe7bf6a2ca32e6642919aea91f072ead8c1.axp">74hc595 shiftregister counter.axp</a> (3.0 KB) </p>

<p>it's a simple cb16 object connected to the SPI out script.<br><img src="//community.axoloti.com/uploads/default/original/1X/2e4902d29975a0ad9f48a57639beea93a399245d.png" width="390" height="384"></p>
          </blockquote>
          <p><a href="https://sebiik.github.io/community.axoloti.com.backup/t/gpio-i-o-example-74hc595-shift-register-spi/131/3">Read full topic</a></p>
